        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>March 1<hi rend="superscript">st</hi> —</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I did receive the Photograph, which you so kindly sent me &amp; have often admired it. Also your interesting paper.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> It was a mere oversight that I did not specially thank you for them.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> But in truth I am so overwhelmed with letters on many days that I am often <hi rend="underline">forced</hi> to be very brief in my answers, &amp; I may appear ungrateful when this is not my frame of mind.</p>
<p>with my apologies &amp; renewed thanks, I remain | My dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p>
<p>P.S. I have lately read your interesting discussion on Prof Weismann’s reviews on Dimorphism in butterflies, &amp; was particularly glad to see that you approve of the essay, which struck me much.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 23, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10328.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Henry Edwards, 26 December 1875</ref>. Edwards sent his paper on the pitcher-plant <hi rend="italic">Darlingtonia californica</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9006.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">H. Edwards 1875</ref>) accompanied by dried specimens and a coloured photograph of the plant. A copy of the paper is in DAR 86: B26. The photograph has not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9216.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Henry Edwards, [after 26 December 1875]</ref> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 23), CD acknowledged Edwards’s offer to supply information and thanked him for a specimen of <hi rend="italic">Darlingtonia</hi>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD evidently mistook <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1470.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Henry Edwards</ref> for <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1472.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Henry Edwards</ref>, who had discussed <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5050.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">August Weismann’s</ref> essay on the seasonal dimorphism of butterflies (Weismann 1875a) in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9007.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">W. H. Edwards 1875</ref>. A copy is in the Darwin Pamphlet Collection–CUL.</note>
        </div>        
            
